m of care; or the foundation of psychoanalytic work on the question of sexuality? Jamieson Webster traces conversion’s shifting meanings—in religious, economic, and even chemical processes—revisiting the work of thinkers as diverse as Benjamin, Foucault, Agamben, and Lacan. She provides an intimate account of her own conversion from patient to psychoanalyst, as well as her continuing struggle to apprehend the complexities of the patient’s body. When listening to dreams, symptoms, worries, or sexual impasses, the body becomes a defining trope that belies a vulnerable and urgent wish for transformation. Conversion Disorder names what is singular about the entanglement of the fractured body and the social world in order to imagine what kind of cure is possible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aConversion disorder. 0aPsychoanalysis. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2018z978311070863908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776940uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/webs1840840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231545310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231545310/original  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-070863-9  CUP Single-User eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles